        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Moor Park, Farnham | Surrey</placeName>
                    <date>Feb. 9<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>Dear Lubbock</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Many thanks for your interesting note.— I am very glad to hear about your brother.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> What a splendid joke about Falconer.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I sh<hi rend="superscript">d</hi>. much like to see the Builder, with Huxley, which shall be returned.—<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>I do not think Instincts present any great difficulty, for they vary &amp; the variations are inherited. Your cases of important organs differing much in (<hi rend="underline">apparently</hi>) allied forms is a much greater &amp; very serious difficulty &amp; I can take refuge only in our ignorance of correlations<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>I have several other letters to write &amp; am as idle as a dog, so Farewell | Yours very truly | C. Darwin</p>
<p>I have despatched letter to Wollaston.—<ref target="#foot.f6"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">3.3 (<hi rend="italic">apparently</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">3.3 very] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year 1859 is the only one in which CD visited Moor Park in February (de Beer ed. 1959).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2408.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Lubbock, [6 February 1859]</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2409.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Lubbock, 8 February 1859</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The reference to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1585.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hugh Falconer</ref> was apparently in the missing portion of the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2409.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Lubbock, 8 February 1859</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">An extract from <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2486.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Henry Huxley’s</ref> closing lecture to working men, delivered at the Government School of Mines in the autumn of 1858, appeared in <hi rend="italic">the Builder</hi>, 15 January 1859,pp. 35–6. It concerned the relationship between science and religion.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2409.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from John Lubbock, 8 February 1859</ref> and n. 3.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">This letter was written in pencil. The letter from Lubbock to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5216.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Vernon Wollaston</ref> has not been found. CD was to forward it to Wollaston (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2408.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Lubbock, [6 February 1859]</ref>).</note>
        </div>        
            
